<div class="step-5">
  <h3> 5. Hardest Decisions</h3>
  <div class="divider3"> </div>
  <div class="project-description">
  For the “Discover” page, we decided to use the overarching design that
  both Spotify and Apple Music had because they were extremely similar.
  However, we chose to use Spotify’s design choice of “Genres” instead
  of “New Music” because we found it is easier for users to search
  through these labels so that they could find music that they would
  like to listen to, instead of just having new popular music show up.
  Then from there, the user would decide whether or not to listen to
  popular playlists or the biggest icons in that specific genre. We
  decided this was the best possible choice for our project mainly
  because this flow of decisions helps the user decide what to do next,
  rather than exploring aimlessly, which Spotify sometimes does.
  </br>
  For adding newly discovered music, we had a little trouble deciding
  which method to use when finding new songs, something like Spotify
  or something like Pandora. We ultimately decided on something like
  Pandora, so that we did not have to deal with the troublesome genre
  lists that occurs when trying to find new music through the “Browse”
  section of Spotify. This was so the user can just focus on listening
  to new music and deciding whether or not to add the song to their playlist.
  The genre list and artist was decided to stay in the “Browse” section of the
  project, so that the user can literally browse all the genres and artists
  when they want, rather than having to find new music through browsing through
  all the songs.

